ithelial human lung NL-20 cells", "obj": "cell_line", "prob": 0.9830240607261658, "span": {"begin": 1459, "end": 1505}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:9606"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "human", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9452523589134216, "span": {"begin": 1483, "end": 1488}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "NSCLC cells", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.8057979941368103, "span": {"begin": 1507, "end": 1518}}, {"id": ["mesh:D002289"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "NSCLC", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.999747097492218, "span": {"begin": 1507, "end": 1512}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:23411"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "SIRT1 protein", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9768133163452148, "span": {"begin": 1553, "end": 1566}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:23411"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "Sirtuin", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9905168414115906, "span": {"begin": 1674, "end": 1681}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:4790"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "NF-kB", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9909759759902954, "span": {"begin": 1715, "end": 1720}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:23411"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "Sirtuins", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9768208265304565, "span": {"begin": 1752, "end": 1760}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3576"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "luciferase reporter", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9775067567825317, "span": {"begin": 1842, "end": 1861}}, {"id": ["mesh:D000077185"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "resveratrol", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.997097373008728, "span": {"begin": 1910, "end": 1921}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:4790"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "NF-kB", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9918776750564575, "span": {"begin": 1939, "end": 1944}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:7124"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "TNFa", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9886642098426819, "span": {"begin": 1985, "end": 1989}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:7124"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "TNFa", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9927214980125427, "span": {"begin": 1991, "end": 1995}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:4790"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "NF-kB", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9932008385658264, "span": {"begin": 2004, "end": 2009}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:23411"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "Sirtuin", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9930618405342102, "span": {"begin": 2067, "end": 2074}}, {"id": ["mesh:D009536"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "nicotinamide", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9988355040550232, "span": {"begin": 2086, "end": 2098}}, {"id": ["mesh:C444426"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "splitomicin", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9993280172348022, "span": {"begin": 2102, "end": 2113}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:4790"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "NF-kB", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9926136136054993, "span": {"begin": 2115, "end": 2120}}, {"id": ["mesh:C012589"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "trichostatin A", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.8009194135665894, "span": {"begin": 2178, "end": 2192}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:46024"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "TSA", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9995279312133789, "span": {"begin": 2194, "end": 2197}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:9734"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "HDAC class I and class II", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.8300067782402039, "span": {"begin": 2203, "end": 2228}}], "text": "According to Lu et al, SIRT1 inhibited the growth of gastric cancer through inhibiting the activation of STAT3 and NF-B (Lu et al.,2014). The goal was to look at SIRT1&#39;s regulatory effects on gastric cancer (GC) cells (AGS and MKN-45) as well as the links between SIRT1 and STAT3 and NF-B activation in GC cells. The SIRT1 activator (resveratrol RSV) was discovered to contribute to the repression of viability and increase of senescence, which was reversed by SIRT1 inhibitor (nicotinamide NA) and SIRT1 depletion using the CCK-8 and SA-&beta;-gal&nbsp;assays, respectively. SIRT1 activation (RSV supplement) reduced not only STAT3 activation, including STAT3 mRNA level, c-myc mRNA level, phosphorylated STAT3 (pSTAT3) proteins, and acetylizad STAT3 (acSTAT3) proteins, but also pNF-B p65 and acNF-B p65 suppression. The effects of RSV were reversed by NA.     Furthermore, when STAT3 or NF-B were knocked down, neither RSV nor NA could affect cellular survival or senescence in MKN-45 cells. Overall, the outcomes of the study revealed that SIRT1 activation could cause GC in vitro to lose viability and senescence. Furthermore, our findings demonstrated that SIRT1 inhibited proliferation in GC cells and was related with deacetylation-mediated suppression of STAT3 and NF-B protein activation.     The levels of SIRT1 protein expression in non-small-cell lung cancer (NSCLC) cell lines were examined in a study by Yeung et al.,2004. In comparison to immortalised epithelial human lung NL-20 cells, NSCLC cells exhibit significant quantities of SIRT1 protein, as reported by other researchers (Luo et al, 2001; Vaziri et al, 2001).     Pharmacological modulators of Sirtuin activity were employed to see if NF-kB transcription was regulated by Sirtuins (Landry et al, 2000; Bedalov et al, 2001; Howitz et al, 2003).&nbsp;   Transient luciferase reporter experiments revealed that cells pretreated with resveratrol had very minimal NF-kB transcription following the presence of TNFa. TNFa-induced NF-kB activity was boosted when cells were pretreated with the Sirtuin inhibitors nicotinamide or splitomicin. NF-kB transcription was also potentiated in cells treated with trichostatin A (TSA), an HDAC class I and class II inhibitor, as expected.", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 15:44:10 +0000 2026"}